# Responsive Design and Spacing Guidelines

## Creating New Page Segments or Pages

When creating new page segments, components, or entire pages, follow these guidelines for consistent, responsive design.

## Mobile-First Responsive Approach

- Always use a mobile-first approach with Tailwind CSS breakpoints
- Start with mobile styles (base), then progressively enhance for larger screens
- Use breakpoints: `sm:` (640px), `md:` (768px), `lg:` (1024px), `xl:` (1280px)

## Centering and Layout

- Use `mx-auto` with `max-w-[1440px]` (or appropriate max-width) to center containers horizontally
- Apply `items-center` and `justify-center` on flex containers to center content
- Never rely solely on padding/margin for horizontal positioning - use centering utilities (`mx-auto`, `items-center`)
- Ensure elements are centered on ALL screen sizes, not just mobile and desktop

## Consistent Padding and Spacing

### Horizontal Padding (Side Padding)

- Use progressive padding that scales smoothly across breakpoints:
  - Base (mobile): `px-4` (16px)
  - Small: `sm:px-6` (24px)
  - Medium: `md:px-8` (32px)
  - Large: `lg:px-[80px]` (80px)
- Apply consistent horizontal padding to all sections: `px-4 sm:px-6 md:px-8 lg:px-[80px]`
- Maintain the same padding values across all components on the same page

### Vertical Spacing Between Sections

- Use consistent vertical spacing that scales responsively:
  - Mobile: `py-[40px]` or `gap-[40px]`
  - Medium: `md:py-[60px]` or `md:gap-[60px]`
  - Large: `lg:py-[80px]` or `lg:gap-[80px]`
- Wrap sections in semantic elements (`<section>`) with consistent padding
- Use `space-y-[40px] md:space-y-[60px] lg:space-y-[80px]` for consistent gaps between child elements

### Internal Component Spacing

- Use responsive gaps: `gap-[20px] md:gap-[30px]` for spacing between elements
- Scale spacing proportionally: smaller on mobile, larger on desktop

## Typography Responsiveness

- Scale typography responsively across breakpoints:
  - Mobile: Base size (e.g., `text-[32px]`)
  - Medium: `md:text-[40px]`
  - Large: `lg:text-[48px]`
- Adjust line-height proportionally: `leading-[44px] md:leading-[56px] lg:leading-[64px]`
- Ensure text remains readable on all screen sizes

## Component Structure

### Section Wrapper Pattern

```tsx
<section className="mx-auto flex w-full max-w-[1440px] flex-col items-center gap-[40px] px-4 py-0 sm:px-6 md:gap-[60px] md:px-8 lg:gap-[80px] lg:px-[80px]">
  {/* Content */}
</section>
```

### Page Layout Pattern

```tsx
<main className="pt-[80px] md:pt-[100px]">
  <section className="py-[40px] md:py-[60px] lg:py-[80px]">
    <Component />
  </section>
</section>
```

## Fixed Navigation Considerations

- When using fixed navigation, add padding-top to main content area
- Use: `pt-[80px] md:pt-[100px]` on the main wrapper to account for fixed navbar
- Ensure fixed elements have proper z-index: `z-50` for navbar, `z-40` for dropdowns

## Responsive Component Patterns

### Cards/Lists

- Stack vertically on mobile: `flex-col md:flex-row`
- Full width on mobile: `w-full md:w-[320px]`
- Responsive gaps: `gap-[20px] md:gap-[30px]`

### Buttons

- Stack vertically on mobile: `flex-col md:flex-row`
- Responsive gaps: `gap-4 md:gap-[50px]`

### Images

- Scale images responsively: `h-[120px] w-[156px] md:h-[172.71px] md:w-[224.73px]`
- Maintain aspect ratios

## Key Principles

1. **Consistency**: Use the same spacing values across all components
2. **Centering**: Always center containers using `mx-auto` and `items-center`
3. **Progressive Enhancement**: Start mobile, enhance for larger screens
4. **Semantic HTML**: Use proper semantic elements (`<main>`, `<section>`, `<nav>`)
5. **Predictable Spacing**: Use consistent spacing scales that users can expect

## SEO and Accessibility Best Practices

Always be SEO-conscious and ensure accessibility when creating new components, segments, or pages.

### Semantic HTML

- Use proper HTML5 semantic elements:
  - `<main>` for main content (one per page)
  - `<section>` for distinct content sections
  - `<nav>` for navigation menus
  - `<header>` for page headers
  - `<footer>` for page footers
  - `<article>` for standalone content
  - `<aside>` for sidebar content
- Avoid using `<div>` when a semantic element is more appropriate
- Use semantic elements to improve SEO and screen reader navigation

### Heading Hierarchy

- Maintain proper heading hierarchy: `h1` → `h2` → `h3` → `h4` → `h5` → `h6`
- Never skip heading levels (e.g., don't go from `h1` directly to `h3`)
- Use only ONE `h1` per page (typically in the hero section)
- Use headings to structure content logically, not for styling
- Headings should describe the content that follows them

### Image Alt Text

- Always provide descriptive `alt` text for all images
- Use `alt=""` (empty string) only for decorative images that don't convey meaning
- Alt text should describe the image's content and purpose
- Include relevant keywords naturally, but prioritize clarity
- For Next.js Image component: always include the `alt` prop

```tsx
// Good: Descriptive alt text
<Image
  alt="Lizardprojects company logo"
  src="/images/logo.svg"
  width={206}
  height={36}
/>

// Good: Empty alt for decorative images
<Image
  alt=""
  src="/images/decorative-icon.svg"
  width={24}
  height={24}
/>
```

### ARIA Labels and Accessibility

- Add `aria-label` to interactive elements without visible text labels
- Use `aria-expanded` for collapsible elements (menus, dropdowns)
- Use `aria-hidden="true"` for decorative elements that should be ignored by screen readers
- Provide `aria-describedby` when additional context is needed
- Use `role` attributes when necessary (but prefer semantic HTML first)

```tsx
// Good: Button with aria-label
<button
  onClick={toggleMenu}
  aria-label="Toggle mobile menu"
  aria-expanded={isMenuOpen}
>
  {/* Icon */}
</button>

// Good: Decorative element with aria-hidden
<div aria-hidden="true">
  {/* Decorative icon that doesn't need screen reader attention */}
</div>
```

### Keyboard Accessibility

- Ensure all interactive elements are keyboard accessible
- Use proper focus states (visible focus indicators)
- Maintain logical tab order
- Provide keyboard shortcuts for common actions when appropriate
- Use `<button>` for buttons, not `<div>` with onClick handlers

### Form Accessibility

- Always associate form inputs with labels using `<label>` or `aria-label`
- Use `aria-required` for required fields
- Provide `aria-describedby` for error messages and help text
- Group related form fields with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`

```tsx
// Good: Properly labeled input
<label htmlFor="email">Email address</label>
<input
  id="email"
  type="email"
  aria-required="true"
  aria-describedby="email-error"
/>

// Or with aria-label
<input
  type="email"
  aria-label="Email address"
  aria-required="true"
/>
```

### Page Structure and Landmarks

- Use HTML5 landmarks to create a clear page structure:
  - `<header>` for site header/navigation
  - `<main>` for main content (one per page)
  - `<nav>` for navigation sections
  - `<section>` for distinct content areas
  - `<footer>` for site footer
- This helps screen readers navigate and improves SEO

### SEO Considerations

- Use descriptive, keyword-rich page titles in `<title>` tags
- Include meta descriptions for pages
- Use proper heading structure for SEO (search engines use headings to understand content hierarchy)
- Ensure images have descriptive filenames when possible
- Use semantic HTML to help search engines understand content structure
- Include structured data (Schema.org) when appropriate

